  "prompt": "What are the rules for Yahoo's fantasy hockey?",
  "response": "Yahoo's fantasy hockey rules can vary slightly depending on the specific league setup and commissioner preferences, but here are the general guidelines:\n\n1. **League Types**: Yahoo offers several types of fantasy hockey leagues, including Head-to-Head, Points, Rotisserie, and Keeper leagues.\n\n2. **Scoring**:\n   - **Head-to-Head (H2H)**: Teams compete against each other in different statistical categories each week. The team with the most categories won receives a win, and the other team gets a loss.\n   - **Points**: Teams accumulate points based on player statistics, and the team with the most points at the end of the season wins.\n   - **Rotisserie (Roto)**: Teams are ranked based on their cumulative stats in various categories throughout the season.\n   - **Categories**: Common categories include goals, assists, plus/minus, penalty minutes, power-play points, hits, and more for skaters. For goalies, categories might include wins, goals against average (GAA), save percentage, and shutouts.\n\n3. **Roster Composition**:\n   - Teams typically have a mix of forwards (centers, left wings, right wings), defensemen, and goalies.\n   - Bench and injured reserve spots allow for flexibility in managing player injuries and off days.\n\n4. **Draft**:\n   - Most leagues hold a live draft before the season starts where managers select players for their teams. This can be done in snake draft format or auction style.\n   - Auto-draft options are also available for managers who can't attend the live draft.\n\n5. **Player Transactions**:\n   - Managers can add and drop players, make trades, and manage their rosters daily or weekly.\n   - Waivers and free-agent pickups are subject to league settings (e.g., waiver priority, free agent budget).\n\n6. **Matchups** (H2H leagues):\n   - Each week, teams are matched up against one another, competing in selected statistical categories. Points are awarded for each category won.\n\n7. **Playoffs**:\n   - Towards the end of the season, top teams usually compete in a playoff bracket to determine the league champion.\n   - Playoff spots and formats can vary based on league settings.\n\n8. **Commissioner Tools**:\n   - League commissioners have access to tools for setting rules, adjusting rosters, and managing the league.\n\n9. **Player Eligibility**:\n   - Players can be assigned to specific positions based on Yahoo's designations. Position eligibility can change throughout the season.\n\n10. **Injuries and Suspensions**:\n   - Managers must navigate player injuries and suspensions, utilizing injured reserve spots if available.\n\nIt's important to refer to the specific rules and settings of your Yahoo fantasy hockey league, as individual leagues can have customized rules that may differ from these general guidelines.",
